All:<br>
<br>
I think this speaks to a roleplay issue that goes beyond acronyms; I think it gets to the role a priest (Shaman, Cleric, Druid) should play, the role alignment plays, and the obligation casters have to buff random people and/or the entitlement of said random people to said buffs.<br>
<br>
I've said this before, and I maintain it now: I believe the proper role of any priest is to protect the faithful and to further their religion.<br>
<br>
Beyond that, I don't believe any caster has any responsibility to others beyond what her or his personality and alignment dictates.  While it would most definitely be in-character for a Discordant Good Enchantress who, who believes in Truth, Beauty, Freedom, and Love, to run around casting Clarity on every caster and priest she meets, it would not be in-character for a Discordant Evil Enchantress, who believes in clawing her way to the top, to do so unless it ultimately served her purposes for getting ahead.  (Please note: I'm not saying either alignment should be played that way.  I'm using alignment in tandem with character traits.  There most certainly can be &quot;grumpy&quot; DGs and &quot;nice&quot; DEs out there.)<br>
<br>
I think it'd be excellent roleplay if, for instance, one were an utterly mercenary caster (probably some variant of Neutral) who charged outrageous prices for popular buffs.<br>
<br>
But I don't think anyone's <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>entitled</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> to anything they cannot do for themselves.  Do I wish I could cast Breeze/Clarity on myself?  All the time; every time I open my spellbook when I'm down at 5-10% mana, in fact.  Do I run around begging for it, complaining about what a jerk so-and-so is if s/he doesn't give it to me?  No, on both counts.<br>
<br>
